	<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-399870">
		<div id="comment-399870">
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/66b49a2c346782470e1b31f42b396015?s=48&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />
			<cite class="fn">Ryan</cite>

			<span class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
				|
				<a href="http://www.thesurvivalpodcast.com/episode-1212-all-about-grills-smokers-and-outdoor-cooking/comment-page-1#comment-399870">
				September 23, 2013 at 6:12 pm</a>
					|
													</span><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-body"><p>I loved the show, I&#8217;m a BIG charcoal griller.  I have a CharGrill from lowes and it has been wonderful.  </p>
<p>On the Chimney&#8217;s for starting coals, my favorite one is the weber brand. instead of a flat plate with holes, it&#8217;s a spiral of wire in a cone shape.  allows for more coals to be started faster.<br />
Also, I stopped using paper to light it, I just set it on the burner for my turkey fryer for about 3 min and the coals are lit, 15 min later they are  ready to be dumped.  Before doing this, I just used the bag the charcoal came it, as I dumped out the coals I would rip off the top part and use it to light the coals.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve thought about the BGE, but can never justify the cost of it, those are might &#8216;spensive.</p>
</div>

