				September 25, 2013 at 9:35 am</a>
					|
													</span><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-body"><p>So you don&#8217;t over cook it and so you get the outside nice and caramelized.  Cooking on open flame you can get the grill really hot but not cook the meat though too fast.  That give you enough time on both sides to get the nice charred, caramelized, grill mark looking deliciousness on the steak.  </p>
<p>I mentioned the way Scotts old style thick aluminum grill made a good steak with the lid down, however it wasn&#8217;t what I call perfect.  It was juicy, it was perfectly medium inside and it did taste very good but it wasn&#8217;t charred and caramelized on the out side.  </p>
<p>Simply put ignore the level of doneness because this might be too rare for your taste, just look at the outsides,</p>
<p>I want this in a steak <a href="http://chicolockersausage.files.wordpress.com/2012/01/grilled-rare-steak.jpg" rel="nofollow">http://chicolockersausage.files.wordpress.com/2012/01/grilled-rare-steak.jpg</a></p>
<p>Not this <a href="https://www.hopeingod.org/sites/hopeingod.org/files/photos/steak.jpg" rel="nofollow">https://www.hopeingod.org/sites/hopeingod.org/files/photos/steak.jpg</a></p>
</div>

